Lastly, we compare FedMGDA+ with existing FL algorithms using different notions of fairness on CIFAR-10. For the first experiment, we adopt the same fairness metric as (Li etÂ al., 2020b, ), and measure fairness by calculating the variance of usersâ€™ test error. We run each algorithm with different hyperparameters, and among the results, we pick the best ones in terms of average accuracy to be shown in FigureÂ 3; full table of results can be found in SectionÂ B.3. From this figure, we observe that (i) FedMGDA+ achieves the best average accuracy while its standard deviation is comparable with that of q-FedAvg; (ii) FedMGDA+ significantly outperforms FedMGDA, which clearly justifies our proposed modifications in AlgorithmÂ 1 to the vanilla MGDA; and
(iii) FedMGDA+ outperforms FedAvg-n, which uses the same normalization step as FedMGDA+, in terms of average accuracy and standard deviation. These observations confirm the effectiveness of FedMGDA+ in inducing fairness. We perform the same experiment on the Federated EMNIST dataset, and observed similar results, which can be found in TableÂ 6 and SectionÂ B.4.
